### 1. One-Line Summary

Rakza 7 is the more balanced and forgiving offensive rubber, while Evolution MX-D is the harder, faster, and more explosive option for advanced topspin and counter-offensive play.

### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown

* **Speed & Gears:**
    * **Low Impact:** Rakza 7 is easier to regulate on normal rally balls and touch attacks, because its response is more even and less jumpy. Evolution MX-D feels calmer than its hardness number suggests, but it still has a stronger built-in kick once you engage the sponge.
    * **Top End:** Evolution MX-D has the higher ceiling. Tibhar rates it OFF+ with speed 130 and a 50.3–52.3° sponge, and match reviews describe it as especially powerful in topspin rallies and from mid-distance. Rakza 7 is still fast, but it is not as brutally strong at full acceleration.
    * **Linearity:** Rakza 7 is the more linear and predictable rubber overall. Evolution MX-D can feel very direct on committed strokes, but its catapult is more pronounced, so the jump from controlled ball to full attack is larger.

* **Spin Mechanics:**
    * **Opening Loop:** Rakza 7 is easier for most players to open with against backspin because the grip is immediate, the arc is safer, and the short game is less tense. Evolution MX-D can open very hard as well, but it rewards a more committed technique and cleaner timing.
    * **Max Spin:** Evolution MX-D has the higher top-end spin when you fully engage the sponge in strong topspin exchanges. Rakza 7 produces very strong spin too, but its advantage is easier spin access and offensive consistency rather than sheer peak rotation.
    * **Topsheet Grip:** Both have strong mechanical grip. Rakza 7 is built around a high-grip topsheet with Power Sponge and high natural-rubber content, while Evolution MX-D combines a very adhering PRO topsheet with Tibhars RED ENERGY SPONGE.

* **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    * **Arc Height:** Rakza 7 generally plays with a more comfortable medium to medium-high arc. Evolution MX-D usually feels flatter and more penetrating in strong rally play, although user reports vary on the exact throw. That flatter, longer ball is one reason MX-D is so good in counter-topspin exchanges.
    * **Safety:** Rakza 7 is safer for over-the-table attacking and everyday rallying. Evolution MX-D is safer when you are the one taking initiative with a full stroke, but less forgiving when you hesitate or play too passively.

* **Feel & Feedback:**
    * **Sensation:** Rakza 7 gives cleaner, more readable feedback and feels more natural for a wide range of players. Evolution MX-D is harder and more loaded, but Tibhar and multiple reviews note that it feels softer than the hardness figure suggests.
    * **Dwell:** Rakza 7 tends to feel like it holds the ball more naturally in controlled topspin and touch play. Evolution MX-D has optimized contact time for power topspin, but the overall sensation is still more explosive than dwell-oriented.

* **Control & Short Game:**
    * **Sensitivity:** Rakza 7 is the easier rubber on serve receive, pushes, and passive control. Its behavior is more forgiving and less catapult-heavy. Evolution MX-D is manageable, but it asks for more focus and finer hand control, especially on long pushes and keeping the ball short.
    * **Touch Play:** Rakza 7 clearly wins here for most players. Yasakas own description highlights sharp serves and short returns, and user feedback repeatedly praises its pushes and blocks. Evolution MX-D can still produce quality short play, but it is not as naturally comfortable in the short game.

* **Blocking & Countering:**
    * **Passive Block:** Rakza 7 is better for simple, compact passive blocks because it stays stable and easy to place. Evolution MX-D can block very well, but close-to-table passive blocking is more sensitive to timing because of the extra catapult.
    * **Active Counter:** Evolution MX-D is superior here. This is one of its defining strengths: powerful counter-topspin, direct counter-drives, and strong mid-distance exchanges. Rakza 7 can counter well, but it is more of an all-round offensive rubber than a pure counter-offensive weapon.

### 3. The Recommendation

* **Choose Rakza 7 if:** you want the easier all-round offensive rubber, value safer opening loops, better short game control, more predictable blocking, and a setup that works for a broader range of intermediate to advanced players.
* **Choose Evolution MX-D if:** you are an advanced attacker who wants a harder OFF+ forehand rubber with a higher top-end, stronger counter-topspin, and more power from mid-distance, and you are comfortable managing extra catapult and a more demanding short game.
